Project 5 - FMT¶

Author - Shekar Roy¶

DOMAIN: Semiconductor manufacturing process¶

CONTEXT: A complex modern semiconductor manufacturing process is normally under constant surveillance via the monitoring of signals/variables collected from sensors and or process measurement points. However, not all of these signals are equally valuable in a specific monitoring system. The measured signals contain a combination of useful information, irrelevant information as well as noise. Engineers typically have a much larger number of signals than are actually required. If we consider each type of signal as a feature, then feature selection may be applied to identify the most relevant signals. The Process Engineers may then use these signals to determine key factors contributing to yield excursions downstream in the process. This will enable an increase in process throughput, decreased time to learning and reduce the per unit production costs. These signals can be used as features to predict the yield type. And by analysing and trying out different combinations of features, essential signals that are impacting the yield type can be identified.¶

Selection of metric: Since the data is highly skewed, I use the area under the precision-recall curve (AUPRC) rather than the conventional area under the receiver operating characteristic (AUROC). This is because the AUPRC is more sensitive to differences between algorithms and their parameter settings rather than the AUROC

Hyper Parameter Tuning for Xg-Boost¶

In [74]:
parameters = [{'max_depth' : [1, 10, 5, 7]}]

grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator = model, param_grid = parameters, scoring = 'accuracy', cv = 2, n_jobs = -1)

grid_search = grid_search.fit(x_train, y_train)

Observation time!¶

First up, the data set is humongous and not at all easy to understand and for a good duration would need a domain expert to help me understand the colums and their usages. what I have done here, is purely based on the analytics shown by the data. since this is a semi conductor manufacturing process data, where things are collected runtime to deduce the quality to be good or not.

univariate and bivariate analysis are difficult to guage as the understanding of data set itself is a question mark. the heat map shows some correlation but the same is not easily deducible. though some columns do show some strong correlations

The dataset has the following characteristics:

- two-class problem 
- an imbalance with a 14:1 skew of pass to fails
- large number of features -- 590
- missing data
- features/columns which do not have sufficient information
- 4% of the columns/features have more than 50% of their records missing
- some columns have constant values

  • Methods

    • We will look at some of the approaches that deal with class imbalance. These can be a cost sensitive learning approach or sampling-based. Will also be working with feature selection methods. This is a list of methods i used:

      • Random Forest variable importance (feature selection)
      • SVM with SMOTE (oversampling minority class/undersampling majority class)
      • SVM, Undersampling and Data Cleaning for Imbalanced Data
      • Random Forest (weighting the classes)

After an exhaustive model building exercise emcompassing undersampling, over sampling, CV and hyper parameter tuning. we will look at the anomaly detection % to select the best model that i would want to pickle up and use on the future data to see how it performs on any unseen data

Scrolling through the model lists , Hyper Parameter Tuning for Support Vector Classifier stands out with the best anomaly detection model with over 90% chance of detecting an anomaly and after consulting with a domain expert on the % success value, we can deploy the same to prod.

I will be pickling the same for further use.

Conclusions¶

  • This was a totally unfamiliar dataset with no column names trying to help with what the data could be, however during model building a lot of important feature were classified by DT, XG, which when we sit with a domain expert and understand the use of the same, will help us make a better model
  • For now, i have concentrated solely in finding the anomaly detection % of the model using different methods and finally come up with the model hyper tuned using GridSearchCV method and that model is able to predict 90+% anomalies which is great start and can be improved on if we get better answers for the below questions.
  • a lot of column had null or 0 value, which was imputed with 0 for model building, but this needs to be cross checked with a domain expert to understand if those columns had any value in model making OR was the approach right, otherwise the model will perform horribly bad on prod datasets and that is a point of failure.
  • the target classes were highly imbalanced as captured, is this expected always
  • PCA or dimensionality reduction is doing no good as first up the data set is unclear in the terms of attributes and the PCA's dataframe would be even bad while trying to explain the model
  • The SVM combined with a sampling strategy holds promise and we will next look at a combination of oversampling (the minority class) and undersampling (the majority class).
